 Step 9: Dashboard APP & View protection
  We will create a dashboard app that unifies app functionalities. 
  It will be a central screen that let's us open any module or view we want

 python manage.py startapp dashboard

 dashboard/views.py
  from django.shortcuts import render
  from django.contrib.auth.decorators import login_required
  
  # Create your views here.
  @login_required
  def dashboard_home(request):
      return render(request, "dashboard_home.html")


  dashboard/urls.py
    from django.urls import path
    from .views import dashboard_home
    
    urlpatterns = [
        path('', dashboard_home)
    ]

  medhahms/urls.py
    from django.contrib import admin
    from django.urls import path, include
    
    
    urlpatterns = [
        path("admin/", admin.site.urls),
        path('patients/', include('patients.urls')),
        path('doctors/', include('doctors.urls')),
        path('dashboard/', include('dashboard.urls')),
        path('', include('marketing.urls')),
        path('', include('users.urls')),
    ]

   Please note that we have protected dashboard_home view route by 
   adding @login_required decorator imported django.contrib.auth.decorators

   Likewise we have added to doctors, patients views as well. 

  Now, lets develop html inside dashboard_home.html

   using AI  we created better styles for patients/templates and doctors/templates
   Inside /dashboard we have links to /patients and /doctors
   Inside /patients and /doctors we have links to back to dashboard

   Note: When user was not loggedin, django sends him to /accounts/login
   When he tried to access any protected route. 
   We can change this in settings.py
   Just add below line:
   LOGIN_URL = '/login/'

  Step 10: Create Appointments App
  python manage.py startapp appointments

  appointments/models.py
  from django.db import models

  # Create your models here.
  class Appointment(models.Model):
      patient = models.ForeignKey('patients.Patient')
      doctor = models.ForeignKey('doctors.Doctor')
      appointment_time = models.DateTimeField()
      appointment_status = models.CharField(max_length=100)
      
  Please note that we have foreign key relations 
  mapped to Appointment. 

   python3 manage.py makemigrations 
  python3 manage.py migrate

  Now, register model in admin.py

  from django.contrib import admin
  from .models import Appointment
  
  # Register your models here.
  admin.site.register(Appointment)

  Note: To support clean representation in django admin for objects
  Add below to patients/models.py and doctors/models.py classes.
  
   def __str__(self):
        return self.name
  
  And below to appointments/models.py class.
  def __str__(self):
        return f"{self.patient} - {self.doctor}"

